{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = At the Existentialist Cafe: Freedom, Being, and Apricot Cocktails | image = File:TheExistentialistCafe.jpg | caption = Cover | author = [[Sarah Bakewell]] | illustrator = Andreas Gurewich | country = United States | language = English | subject = [[Existentialism]] | publisher = [[Other Press]] | pub_date = 2016 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]]) | pages = 448 | isbn = 978-1590514887 }}
'''''At the Existentialist Cafe: Freedom, Being, and Apricot Cocktails''''' is a 2016 book written by [[Sarah Bakewell]] that covers the philosophy and history of the 20th century movement [[existentialism]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bakewell|first1=Sarah|title=At the Existentialist Cafe: Freedom, Being, and Apricot Cocktails|date=2016|publisher=Other Books|location=New York, New York|edition=1st|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref>
== Summary== Bakewell structures ''At the Existentialist Cafe'' by focusing each chapter on a particular philosopher or time period within the existentialist movement first starting by introducing the early existentialists [[Kierkegaard]], [[Nietzsche]], [[Dostoevsky]], and [[Kafka]] and then moving onto the lives and philosophies of [[Heidegger]], [[Husserl]], [[Sartre]], [[Simone de Beauvoir|Beauvoir]], [[Albert Camus|Camus]], [[Karl Jaspers]], and [[Merleau-Ponty]]. == Bibliography== *{{cite book|last1=Bakewell|first1=Sarah|title=At the Existentialist Cafe: Freedom, Being, and Apricot Cocktails|date=2016|publisher=Other Books|location=New York, New York|edition=1st|accessdate=13 January 2018}} *{{cite web|last1=Hussey|first1=Andrew|title=At the Existentialist Café: Freedom, Being, and Apricot Cocktails by Sarah Bakewell – review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/feb/28/existentialist-cafe-freedom-being-apricot-cocktails-sarah-bakewell-review|website=The Guardian|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=13 January 2018|date=28 February 2016}} *{{cite web|last1=Maslin|first1=Janet|title=Review: In Sarah Bakewell’s ‘At the Existentialist Café,’ Nothingness Has a Certain Something|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/03/books/review-in-sarah-bakewells-at-the-existentialist-cafe-nothingness-has-a-certain-something.html|website=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=13 January 2018|date=2 March 2016}} *{{cite web|last1=Golson|first1=Richard|title=Life and Death at the Existentialist Café - Los Angeles Review of Books|url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/life-and-death-at-the-existentialist-cafe/|website=Los Angeles Review of Books|publisher=LA Review of Books|accessdate=13 January 2018}} *{{cite web|last1=Long|first1=Karen|title=The existentialists come alive (over cocktails) in Sarah Bakewell's 'At the Existentialist Cafe'|url=http://www.latimes.com/books/la-ca-jc-existentialist-cafe-20160306-story.html|website=Los Angeles Times|publisher=LA Ti