{{philo-stub}}

{{short description|The hypothetical ability of the human species to choose what they will become}}

Conscious evolution refers to the ability of the human species to choose what the species [[Homo sapiens|''Homo sapiens'']] will become in the future, based on recent advancements in science, medicine, technology, psychology, sociology, and spirituality. Most leading thinkers in this area have focused on the conscious evolution of how we think, live, organize ourselves, work together, and address issues, rather than on [[evolution|biological evolution]]. 

The idea of conscious evolution is not a specific theory, but it has loose connections to [[Ervin László|integral theory]], [[Spiral Dynamics]], and [[noosphere]] thought.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.consciouslifestylemag.com/conscious-evolution-save-humanity-planet/|title=Eco-Futurist Creates Revolutionary 10 Point Plan To Save Humanity & The Planet|date=2015-11-28|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref> It is also sometimes connected to the theory of the [[global brain]] or [[collective consciousness]].<ref name=":0" /> Some have suggested “conscious cultural-evolution”<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2005-04-01|title=Accounting’s contribution to a conscious cultural evolution: an end to sustainable development|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1045235403000236|journal=Critical Perspectives on Accounting|language=en|volume=16|issue=3|pages=185–208|doi=10.1016/S1045-2354(03)00023-6|issn=1045-2354}}</ref> as a more accurate term, to reduce association with standard [[Evolution|biological evolution]], though this is not widely applied.

Conscious evolution suggests that now that humanity is conscious of its history and of how things evolve (evolutionary consciousness), and given the rapid pace of change in society and culture, humanity can (and should) choose advancement through co-operation, co-creation and sustainable practices over self-destruction through separateness, competition, and ecological devastation.

== Conscious Evolution - A Mechanism ==

At the centre of the concept of conscious evolution are the approximate definitions of the term’s constituent phenomena ('[[consciousness]]' and '[[evolution]]'). However, the term implies more than these phenomena generally encompass, not least as it is often used with strong assumptions of a collective interest/ common good.

Evolution does not exclusively act upon [[Morphology (biology)|morphological]] ([[Phenotype|phenotypic]]) variation; it can also work on a cognitive level.<ref name=":1" /> [[Daniel Dennett]] has suggested that evolution is simply a process which uses [[natural selection]] as a basic [[algorithm]] for progression.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=Darwin's Dangerous Idea|last=Dennett|first=Daniel|publisher=Simon & Schuster|year=1995|isbn=0-684-82471-X|location=|pages=}}</ref> This could be applied to changes in behaviours, practices, concepts, theories and ideas ([[cultural evolution]]). In these situations the mutating [[The Selfish Gene#"Replicators"|replicators]] of evolution can be considered [[Meme|memes]] (theoretical units of cultural information)<ref>{{Cite book|title=The selfish gene|last=Dawkins|first=Richard|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1978|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> rather than [[Gene|genes]]. Over the last 10,000 years humanity is increasingly capable of influencing its own environment and cognitively adapting to these environmental changes through the use of evolving [[Meme|memes]]. [[Memetics|Memetic]] (cognitive) innovation (as opposed to morphological variation) has therefore become the primary driver of humanity’s [[Evolution|evolutionary success]].<ref name=":1" /> 

Humans are ‘[[Consciousness|conscious]]’, and are consciously manipulating the [[Meme|memes]] they use. Consciousness itself (in humans’ brains) can therefore be said to have agency over its own evolution, because [[Memetics|memetic]] usage influences evolutionary success. Evolution is also something humans are conscious of. Consciousness (in human brains) can therefore be simultaneously conscious of evolution (working in this case upon [[Meme|memes]]) while consciously manipulating its own [[memetics]], in order to influence its own [[evolution]]. Evolution (in the sense of its impact upon [[memetics]]) is therefore increasingly a subject of knowledge, rather than an unknown pressure operating on the world.<ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|last=Banathy|first=Bela H.|date=2003-01-16|title=Self-guided/conscious evolution|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/pdf/10.1002/sres.506|journal=Systems Research and Behavioral Science|language=en|volume=20|issue=4|pages=309–321|doi=10.1002/sres.506|issn=1092-7026}}</ref>

== Conscious Evolution - Writers and Thinkers ==

Conscious evolution is largely the output of several luminaries’ personal evolutionary journeys<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=http://integralleadershipreview.com/11697-integral-conscious-evolution/|title=8/15 – Integral Conscious Evolution - Integral Leadership Review|last=Taborga|first=Jorge|date=|website=integralleadershipreview.com|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref>. The central objective is to achieve a globally sustainable future by developing the idea that humans can guide evolution, now that we are conscious of it (evolutionary consciousness)<ref name=":3" />. Owing to the broad definition of the term, numerous writers and thinkers, from a range of fields and backgrounds have contributed ideas to the concept of conscious evolution. These include; [[Erich Jantsch]], [[Teilhard de Chardin]], [[Jonas Salk]], [[Ervin Laszlo]], [[Mihaly Csikszentmihaly]], [[Bela H. Banathy]], [[Barbara Marx Hubbard]], [[Andrew Cohen (spiritual teacher)|Andrew Cohen]], [[David Bohm#Consciousness and thought|David Bohm]], [[Eric Chaisson]], [[Duane Elgin]], [[Brian Swimme]], [[Ken Wilber]], [http://integralleadershipreview.com/11697-integral-conscious-evolution/ Jorge Taborga] and others.

One of the earliest uses of the phrase 'conscious evolution' may be that of [[Mary Parker Follett]] in 1918: ''"Conscious evolution means giving less and less place to herd instinct and more to the group imperative. We are emerging from our gregarious condition and are now to enter on the rational way of living by scanning our relations to one another, instead of bluntly feeling them, and so adjusting them that unimpeded progress on this higher plane is secured''.''"'' (''The New State'', p. 91)

Human evolution, has thus far been the consequence of billions of random events and chance interactions (as opposed to a planned endeavour).<ref name=":4">{{Cite book|title=The Evolving Self: A Psychology for the New Millenium|last=Csikszentmihalyi|first=M.|publisher=Harper Perennial|year=1993|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> Given that humans have knowledge of this evolutionary process (evolutionary consciousness) it is the task of humanity to take control of these random changes, to avoid the '[[Extinction|disastrous fate]]' (extinction) that has befallen the majority of species that have ever existed.<ref name=":4" /> This idea that evolutionary consciousness should be used as a tool, or even an argument for self-guided evolution, is a major central theme of the concept of conscious evolution. [[Béla H. Bánáthy|Bela H. Banathy]] <ref name=":2" /> captures this sentiment succinctly in his paper ''Self guided/conscious evolution'': ''“Our consciousness of evolution becomes a springboard for leaping into conscious evolution.”''<ref name=":2" /> The issue then arises of how humanity can be expected to know how it should use its recently acquired evolutionary consciousness to select the best evolutionary path.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":5">{{Cite book|title=Anatomy of Reality: Merging Intuition and Reason|last=Salk|first=J.|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=1983|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> [[Jonas Salk|Jonas Salks]]<ref name=":5" /> is optimistic that humanity is capable of merging intuition with reason in order to find the path that leads to conscious evolution: ''“It now remains for human beings to decide the ultimate course of human evolution. By imagining ourselves inside the process of evolution and by imagining the process of evolution working inside our minds, we may discover how to deal with the opportunities that might influence the direction of evolutionary choices.”''<ref name=":5" />

[[Tom Atlee|Co-intelligence]]; a form of [[group intelligence]] that incorporates group wisdom for the benefit of humanity, is a concept [[Tom Atlee]] has stressed as an essential foundation for conscious evolution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Atlee|first=Tom|date=2008|title=Co-intelligence, Collective Intelligence, and Conscious Evolution|url=https://co-intelligence.org/AtleeInSteeleCI-Bk.doc|journal=Collective Intelligence: Creating a Prosperous World at Peace|volume=Earth Intelligence Network|pages=5-14|via=}}</ref> [[Tom Atlee|Atlee]] suggested that many of the factors of [[Tom Atlee|co-intelligence]] (wisdom, intentionality, choice, awareness) could be used as tools to enhance consciousness and improve shared circumstances. [[Eric Chaisson]] similarly identified ‘knowledge’ and ‘compassion’ as key guiding forces for the future,<ref name=":6">{{Cite book|title=The Life Era|last=Chaisson|first=E.|publisher=The Atlantic Monthy Press|year=1987|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> stating in 1987 that we must “act wisely, quite beyond intelligently, in order to achieve successful ethical evolution”.<ref name=":6" /> [[Eric Chaisson|Chaisson’s]] main emphasis, however, was on [[ethics]], which he argued was the most important focus for ensuring effective conscious evolution: ''“if our species is to survive to enjoy the future, then we must make synonymous the words ‘future’ and ‘ethical,’ thus terming our next evolutionary epoch ‘ethical evolution’”''.<ref name=":6" />

Numerous aspects of both [[Tom Atlee|co-intelligence]] and [[ethics]], in our self-guided, conscious evolution are also present in the writings of [[Barbara Marx Hubbard]], one of the most widely published advocates of conscious evolution. [[Barbara Marx Hubbard|Hubbard]] has a positive opinion of humanity and the evolutionary process.<ref name=":7">{{Cite book|title=Conscious Evolution|last=Hubbard|first=B.|publisher=New World Library|year=1996|isbn=|location=Novato, CA|pages=}}</ref> She has claimed that: “Every tendency in us leads us toward greater wholeness, unity, and connectedness... Integration is inherent in the process of evolution.”<ref name=":7" /> However, Hubbard has been criticised for focusing on the most hopeful evidence that conscious evolution is taking humanity in a positive direction.<ref name=":8">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottlondon.com/reviews/hubbard.html|title=Conscious Evolution :: A Book Review by Scott London|last=London|first=Scott|website=www.scottlondon.com|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref> Scott London commented in a review of her 1998 book ''Conscious Evolution; Awakening the Power of Our Social Potential'', that much of the evidence provided was ''“soft data”'', ''“highly questionable”'', or ''“anecdotal”''.<ref name=":8" /> Despite these criticisms [[Barbara Marx Hubbard|Hubbard]], and numerous other advocates of conscious evolution, are continuing to promote the concept, with some suggesting it be included in education and government<ref name=":0" />.

