{{improvereferences |date=November 2011}} The '''Dyad''' is a title used by the [[Pythagoreans]] for the number two, representing the principle of "twoness" or "otherness".
[[Numenius of Apamea]], a [[Neopythagoreanism|Neopythagorean]] philosopher in the latter 2nd century CE, said that [[Pythagoras]] gave the name of [[Monad (Greek philosophy)|Monad]] to God, and the name of Dyad to matter.<ref>[[Chalcidius]] r.52, 5–24, as cited in {{cite book |author=Kahn, Charles N. |title=Pythagoras and the Pythagoreans: a brief history |publisher=Hackett Pub |location=Indianapolis, IN |year=2001 |isbn=0-87220-575-4 |oclc= |doi= |page=172}}</ref>{{Quotation needed|date=October 2010}} Aristotle equated matter as the formation of the elements (energies) into the material world as the static material was formed by the energies being acted upon by force or motion.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} Later [[Neoplatonism|Neoplatonic]] Philosophers and [[idealism|idealists]] like [[Plotinus]] treated the dyad as a second cause ([[demiurge]]),{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}} which was the divine mind ([[nous]]) that via a reflective nature{{Clarification needed|date=October 2010}} ([[Wikt:finite|finiteness]]) causes matter to "appear" or become perceivable.
